  "title": "Pole and Polar",
  "concepts": [
    {
      "title": "Equation and properties",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Pole and Polar&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>If through a point $\\text{P}$ (within or outside a circle) there be drawn any straight line to meet the circle in $\\text{Q}$ and $\\text{R}$, the locus of the point of intersection of the tangents at $\\text{Q}$ and $\\text{R}$ is called the polar of $\\text{P}$; also $\\text{P}$ is called the pole of the polar.</p><p>The equation to the polar of the point $\\left( {{x}_{1}},{{y}_{1}} \\right)$ with respect to the circle ${{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}={{a}^{2}}$.</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"336\" height=\"172\"></p><p>$\\text{x}{{\\text{x}}_{1}}+\\text{y}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}={{\\text{a}}^{2}}$</p><p>In a similar manner it may be proved that the polar of $\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}},{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)$ with respect to the circle.</p><p>${{\\text{x}}^{2}}+{{\\text{y}}^{2}}+2\\text{gx}+2\\text{fy}+\\text{c}=0$</p><p>is $\\text{x}{{\\text{x}}_{1}}+\\text{y}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}+\\text{g}\\left( \\text{x}+{{\\text{x}}_{1}} \\right)+\\text{f}\\left( \\text{y}+{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)+\\text{c}=0$</p><p><strong>To find the pole of a given line with respect to any circle</strong></p><p>Let the equation to the given line be</p><p>$\\text{Ax}+\\text{By}+\\text{C}=0$ … (1)</p><p>1. Let the equation to the circle be,</p><p>${{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}={{a}^{2}}$</p><p>and let the required pole be $\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}},{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)$</p><p>Then, (1) must be the equation to the polar of $\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}},{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)$, i.e., it is the same as the equation.</p><p>$\\text{x}{{\\text{x}}_{1}}+\\text{y}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}-{{\\text{a}}^{2}}=0$ …. (2)</p><p>Comparing equations (1) and (2), we have</p><p>$\\frac{{{\\text{x}}_{1}}}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ A}}=\\frac{{{\\text{y}}_{1}}}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ B}}=\\frac{-{{\\text{a}}^{2}}}{\\text{C}}$</p><p>so that</p><p>${{\\text{x}}_{1}}=\\frac{\\text{A}}{\\text{C}}{{\\text{a}}^{2}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ and }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{y}}_{1}}=-\\frac{\\text{B}}{\\text{C}}{{\\text{a}}^{2}}$</p><p>The required pole is therefore, the point</p><p>$\\left( -\\frac{\\text{A}}{\\text{C}}{{\\text{a}}^{2}},-\\frac{\\text{B}}{\\text{C}}{{\\text{a}}^{2}} \\right)$</p><p>Let the equation to the circle be</p><p>${{\\text{x}}^{2}}+{{\\text{y}}^{2}}+2\\text{gx}+2\\text{fy}+\\text{c}=0$</p><p>If $\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}},{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)$ be the required pole, then (1) must be equivalent to the equation,</p><p>$\\text{x}{{\\text{x}}_{1}}+\\text{y}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}+\\text{g}\\left( \\text{x}+{{\\text{x}}_{1}} \\right)+\\text{f}\\left( \\text{y}+{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)+\\text{c}=0$ … (3)</p><p>$\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ i}\\text{.e}\\text{., }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$ $\\text{x}\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}}+\\text{g} \\right)+\\text{y}\\left( {{\\text{y}}_{1}}+\\text{f} \\right)+\\text{g}{{\\text{x}}_{1}}+\\text{f}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}+\\text{c}=0$</p><p>Comparing (1) with (3), we therefore, have</p><p>$\\frac{{{x}_{1}}+g}{A}=\\frac{{{y}_{1}}+f}{B}=\\frac{g{{x}_{1}}+f{{y}_{1}}+c}{C}$</p><p>By solving these equations, we have the values of ${{x}_{1}}$ and ${{y}_{1}}$.</p><p>If the polar of a point $P$ pass through a point $T$, then the polar of $T$ passes through $P$.</p><p>Let $\\text{P}$ and $\\text{T}$ be the points $\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}},{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)$ and $\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{2}},{{\\text{y}}_{2}} \\right)$ respectively.</p><p>The polar of $\\left( {{x}_{1}},{{y}_{1}} \\right)$ with respect to the circle ${{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}={{a}^{2}}$ is,</p><p>$\\text{x}{{\\text{x}}_{1}}+\\text{y}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}={{\\text{a}}^{2}}$</p><p>This straight line passes through the point $\\text{T}$ if,</p><p>${{\\text{x}}_{2}}{{\\text{x}}_{1}}+{{\\text{y}}_{2}}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}={{\\text{a}}^{2}}$</p><p>Since the relation (1) is true, it follows that the point $\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}},{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)$, i.e., $\\text{P}$, lies on the straight line $\\text{x}{{\\text{x}}_{2}}+\\text{y}{{\\text{y}}_{2}}={{\\text{a}}^{2}}$, which is the polar of $\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{2}},{{\\text{y}}_{2}} \\right)$, i.e., $\\text{T}$, with respect to the circle.</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dd31c03b9dcaf1afe9b7"
    }
